### Code Diary Entry – Improving Our HTML Structure

During the development of our website, our initial approach was to structure the layout mainly using `<div>` elements. This is a very common method and works well for organizing content visually.

However, while researching and learning more about modern web development practices, we discovered that newer semantic HTML elements such as `<main>`, `<section>`, `<article>`, `<header>`, and `<footer>` are now considered best practice.

Because of this, we decided to rethink our approach and would like to introduce these semantic tags into our project from now on. Instead of relying heavily on generic `<div>` elements, we aim to structure our website using meaningful HTML elements that better describe the content.

This change does not only bring advantages, but also follows the current web standard. Semantic HTML improves:
- readability of the code  
- accessibility (especially for screen readers)  
- SEO (search engine optimization)  
- maintainability of the project  

For these reasons, we want to implement this approach directly moving forward and build our pages using semantic structure from the beginning.
